{"Body": "&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://www.universitytimes.ie/?attachment_id=4907\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-4907\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-4907 aligncenter\" title=\"Braco and Burke\" src=\"http://www.universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Braco-and-Burke.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"338\" height=\"450\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>R\u00f3n\u00e1n Burtenshaw</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>Deputy Editor</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">During the month of October, the main fa\u00e7ade at Trinity College Dublin will, for the first time in its 420-year history, form a unique backdrop to an artwork created specifically for the university as part of Dublin Contemporary 2011.</p>\nIreland is currently staging the first international contemporary art exhibition to permeate and pulsate through the capital and beyond, featuring over 114 Irish and international artists. At the heart of the city stands Trinity College and for a period of one month the principal College Green face of the university will display the latest work by Paris based, Yugoslavian born artist\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/artcollections/assets/pdf/DIMITRIJEVIC-Braco-Trinity.pdf\">Braco Dimitrijevi? entitled &lsquo;Casual Passer-by I met at 3.46 PM, Dublin 2011&rsquo;(Download artist's biography, pdf 392kb)</a>.\n\nIn addition to this artwork and in association with Dublin Contemporary 2011, the campus will play host to a <a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/artcollections/assets/pdf/Dublin-Contemporary-Trinity-events.pdf\">programme</a>\u00a0of talks, tours, discussions, and performances organised by the College Art Collections and the Department of the History of Art and Architecture, aided by the Student Visual Arts Society and supported by the Trinity Creative Arts Technologies and Culture initiative\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/catc\">www.tcd.ie/catc\u00a0</a>Shows and events are also underway at\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/artcollections/exhibitions/www.douglashydegallery.com\">The Douglas Hyde Gallery</a>\u00a0and\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/artcollections/exhibitions/www.sciencegallery.com/events\">The Science Gallery</a>.\n\nThese include an opportunity to join the Curator&rsquo;s tour of Trinity College&rsquo;s art collections on Thursday 6th October at 6pm; a panel discussion led by the Dublin Contemporary Irish and international curatorial team on Wednesday 12th October at 7pm; a one-off performance piece related to\u00a0<a href=\"http://www.tcd.ie/artcollections/assets/pdf/Dublin-Contemporary-Hello-Sam.pdf\">'Hello Sam' by Brian O'Doherty, Joe Stanley and Christina Kennedy</a>, through the campus to the National Gallery on the 13th October as a prelude to a chance to meet the artist, critic and Booker prize nominated novelist Brian O&rsquo;Doherty / Patrick Ireland on Friday 14th October where he will perform one of his &lsquo;Vowel Poems&rsquo;; an invitation to celebrate the launch of The Science Gallery&rsquo;s new exhibition &lsquo;Surface Tension: The Future of Water&rsquo; on Thursday 20th October from 6pm; and on Wednesday 2nd November, a talk by Jeremy Lewison, curator of The Douglas Hyde Gallery exhibition, &lsquo;Alice Neel: Family&rsquo;.", "Imageurl": "4907", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "4906", "Heading": "Trinity's main facade the backdrop for a passer-by's face"}